Operationally, this decree is stronger than the earlier draft because it adds three things:

1) accredited third-party testing in Milan and Bologna;
2) public disclosure through a registry;
3) an adaptation fund for the industrial base.

That combination reduces ambiguity. For stores, the main benefit is that objections can be answered with evidence, not slogans.

What still needs watching:
- how strict the pilot criteria are in practice;
- whether the registry is easy for frontline teams to use;
- whether the fund reaches the suppliers that actually need conversion support;
- whether artisanal districts are given a credible transition path, not just reassurances.

My position is slightly more positive, but still conditional. If the label improves product trust and the transition fund supports execution, it can work. If it becomes only a communications tool, it will fail quickly on the shop floor.
